<h2>PHP $_GET</h2>
<p>PHP $_GET can also be used to collect form data after submitting an HTML form 
with method=&quot;get&quot;.</p>
<p>$_GET can also collect data sent in the URL.</p>
<p>Assume we have an HTML page that contains a hyperlink with parameters:</p>
<div class="code notranslate"><div>
&lt;html&gt;<br>
&lt;body&gt;<br><br>
&lt;a href=&quot;test_get.php?subject=PHP&amp;web=W3schools.com&quot;&gt;Test $GET&lt;/a&gt;<br><br>
&lt;/body&gt;<br>
&lt;/html&gt;
</div></div>
<p>When a user clicks on the link &quot;Test $GET&quot;, the parameters &quot;subject&quot; and 
&quot;web&quot; is sent to &quot;test_get.php&quot;, and you can then acces their values 
in &quot;test_get.php&quot; with $_GET.</p>
<p>The example below shows the code in &quot;test_get.php&quot;:</p>

<div class="example">
<h2 class="example">Example</h2>
<div class="example_code notranslate">
&lt;html&gt;<br>
&lt;body&gt;<br>
<br>
	&lt;?php <br>echo &quot;Study &quot; . $_GET['subject'] . &quot; at &quot; . $_GET['web'];<br>?&gt;<br>
<br>
&lt;/body&gt;<br>
&lt;/html&gt;</div>
<br><a class="showbtn" href="showphp.asp?filename=demo_global_get" target="_blank">Run example &raquo;</a>
</div>
